Functions, part 2

Week 4.2

Daniel Anderson
CourseR

Today's Agenda

  • Classes and methods (object oriented programming)
  • Scoping
  • Infix functions
  • Storing and applying functions with source()

Objects

  • Every object has a class and a method. This is generally true of all object-oriented (OO) programming, and not specific to R.
  • R has 3 systems, which differ in the way classes and methods are implemented: S3, S4, and Reference Classes (RC).
  • S3 is the is simplest and most widely used OO system. This is where we will focus most of our attention.


Note that a lot of this section is based on Wickham (2014), Chapter 7. Available online at http://adv-r.had.co.nz/OO-essentials.html

Classes

  • Use class() to determine the class
d <- read.csv("./data/longley.csv")
mod <- lm(Employed ~ Population, 
            data = d)
class(mod)

## [1] "lm"

print(mod)

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Employed ~ Population, data = d)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)   Population  
##      8.3807       0.4849
  • Redefine the class
class(mod) <- "data.frame"
print(mod)

##  [1] coefficients  residuals     effects       rank          fitted.values
##  [6] assign        qr            df.residual   xlevels       call         
## [11] terms         model        
## <0 rows> (or 0-length row.names)
  • The print() function now tries to use the data.frame method for the generic print() function, rather thant the lm method for print().

However, note that the data are still there (the generic function calls are just using the data.frame class, rather than the lm class).

mod$coefficients

## (Intercept)  Population 
##   8.3806742   0.4848781

Our function for today

Simulating dice rolls with the sample() function

?sample
# x = numbers of the die
# size = number of dice
# replace = can a number be sampled more than once?

Roll two dice with six sides

sample(x = 1:6, size = 2, replace = TRUE)

## [1] 1 6

Wrap it in a function

What should the formals be?

t(replicate(100, sample(x = 1:6, size = 2, replace = TRUE)))

dice() function

dice <- function(nsides, nrolls, ndice) {
    experiment <- t(replicate(nrolls, sample(1:nsides, ndice, replace = TRUE)))

return(experiment)
}

Test it out

rolls <- dice(4, 1e5, 3)

Back to classes

Defining class for the dice() function

dice <- function(nsides, nrolls, ndice) {
    experiment <- t(replicate(nrolls, sample(1:nsides, ndice, replace = TRUE)))

return(structure(experiment, class = "dice"))
}

rolls <- dice(4, 1e5, 3)
class(rolls)

## [1] "dice"

Defining methods

Now, because we have a class, we can define a method. Let's define a generic plot function for objects of class "dice"

plot.dice <- function(x) {
    tot <- rowSums(x)

    par(mfrow = c(2, 1), 
        oma = c(5, 4, 1, 0), # outer margins
        mar = c(0, 0, 1, 1)) # margins for each plot
    hist(tot, 
        main = "Histogram of Sum of Simulated Dice Rolls", 
        xlab = "Sum of each roll")
            abline(v = mean(tot), col = "red", lwd = 3)
            abline(v = mean(tot) - sd(tot), col = "gray", lwd = 2, lty = 2)
            abline(v = mean(tot) + sd(tot), col = "gray", lwd = 2, lty = 2)
    boxplot(tot, horizontal = TRUE, frame = FALSE)
}

plot(rolls)

Set generic summary method for class "dice"

summary.dice <- function(x) {
    cat("First 6 Rolls", "", sep = "\n")
    print(x[1:6, ])

    cat("", "Frequencies of Sums", sep = "\n")
    print(table(rowSums(x)))

    cat("", "Frequency of Roll Patterns", sep = "\n")

    print(table(apply(x, 1, paste0, collapse = "")))


return(invisible(list(
            SumFrequencies = table(rowSums(x)), 
            PatternFrequencies = table(apply(x, 1, paste0, collapse = ""))
            )
        )
    )
}

Other options

For the S3 system, there are other (potentially better) ways to set classes and generic functions. For example

dice <- function(nsides, nrolls, ndice) UseMethod("dice")

dice.default <- function(nsides, nrolls, ndice) {
    experiment <- t(replicate(nrolls, sample(1:nsides, ndice, replace = TRUE)))

return(structure(experiment, class = "dice"))
}
dice(8, 5, 4)

##      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
## [1,]    7    6    2    4
## [2,]    2    4    2    2
## [3,]    2    2    2    3
## [4,]    6    1    4    6
## [5,]    4    7    6    6
## attr(,"class")
## [1] "dice"

Dice game

dice.game <- function(x) {
    roll <- as.vector(dice.default(6, 1, x))
    fives <- (roll == 5) * 50
    ones <- (roll == 1) * 100
    if(sum(table(roll) == 3) > 0) {
        threeKind <- (table(roll) == 3)[table(roll) == 3] * 
                (as.numeric(names(table(roll)))[table(roll) == 3] * 100)
        return(sum(fives, ones, threeKind))
    }
    else {
        return(sum(fives, ones))
    }
} 

trial <- 6
class(trial) <- "game"
dice(trial)

## [1] 150

Summary: Classes and Methods

  • Class is metadata that defines the type of object
  • Method is a specific function linked to the class, often constructed through generic functions.
  • Having an understanding of classes and methods can be really helpful when writing packages (although there are packages that make writing packages easier).
  • You may want to think about some default plot, print, or summary methods for your functions, especially if you're applying them regularly.

Lexical Scoping

Lexical scoping

  • Search for symbols (objects) based on the nesting of how they were created, not how they were called.
  • You can generally determine how a value is being called by inspecting the function.

Name masking

R will look within the current environment when objects are called. If it can't find them, it will look one level "up".

y <- 7

foo <- function(x) {
    x + y
}
foo(3); foo(5)

## [1] 10

## [1] 12

foo2 <- function(x) {
    y <- rnorm(10, 100, 5)
    x + y
} 
foo2(3)

##  [1] 104.43577 108.57817  99.23237  97.62022 111.08032 106.93549 107.34238
##  [8] 104.22552  98.47089 102.15222

More on name masking

z <- 1e9
b <- function(x) {
    y <- rnorm(length(x), 100, 10)

    lm <- function(x) {
        z <- 2
        (-1*x)/z
    }
    lm(y)
}

b(1:3)

## [1] -40.87731 -55.34002 -54.54124

a <- function(x) x^2

f <- function(x) {
    a <- function(y) {
        z <- rnorm(length(y), 
                    mean(y, na.rm = TRUE), 
                    sd(y, na.rm = TRUE)
                    )
        x + z
    }
return(4 + a(x))
}
f(2:4)

## [1]  9.96897 10.43472 10.47135

Infix operators

What is an infix operator?

Infix operators are functions that do not require the name of the function precedes the arguments. Infix operators come between two arguments.

Built-in infix functions

There are numerous built-in infix operators (see http://bxhorn.com/data-infix-operators-in-r/)

Create your own infix functions

Let's create an infix operator that returns a logical vector corresponding to whether a given value (within a vector) is within the range of a different vector.

`%w%` <- function(x, vector) {
    x >= min(vector, na.rm = TRUE) & x <= max(vector, na.rm = TRUE)
}

5:10 %w% 8:70

## [1] FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE

8:70 %w% 5:10

##  [1]  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE
## [12] FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE
## [23] FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE
## [34] FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE
## [45] FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE
## [56] FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE

Another example

Now we'll create an infix operator that returns summary information on the relation between two vectors.

`%smry%` <- function(x, y) {
    if(length(x) != length(y)) {
        stop("Vectors must be of the same length")
    }
    cat(
        paste("Covariance =", cov(x, y, use = "complete.obs")),
        paste("Correlation =", cor(x, y, use = "complete.obs")),
        paste("Proportion x cases above Mean of y =", 
            (table(x > mean(y, na.rm = TRUE)) / length(x))[2] ),
        paste("Proportion x cases within the range of y =", 
            (table(x %w% y) / length(x))[2] ),
        sep = "\n")
}

Example continued

a <- rnorm(1e5, 100, 5)
b <- rnorm(1e5, 105, 5)

a %smry% b

## Covariance = 0.00879650781191186
## Correlation = 0.000351467566649441
## Proportion x cases above Mean of y = 0.15951
## Proportion x cases within the range of y = 0.99951

b %smry% a

## Covariance = 0.00879650781191186
## Correlation = 0.000351467566649441
## Proportion x cases above Mean of y = 0.84078
## Proportion x cases within the range of y = 0.99941

Using source() with functions

Next best thing to a package: source()

When you have a function, or set of function to apply, but you want to keep your code tidy, you can store just the function in a separate script and access it via source(). This is most helpful when you have a function that you apply regularly across multiple scripts. 

?source

Function for source file

  1. Write a function
    • Below is a function I apply regularly to batch load a set of csv files into a list.
  2. Save it as a separate R script
readFiles <- function(dir, ...) {
    oldDir <- getwd() # Get current working directory
    setwd(as.character(dir)) # Change directory to where data are stored

    files <- list.files(...) # List all the files in the directory
    dl <- sapply(1:length(files), function(i) read.csv(files[i])) # Read data
    names(dl) <- substr(files, 1, nchar(files) - 4) # Name the elements of the list according to the filename

on.exit(setwd(oldDir)) # Reset the working directory
return(dl) # Return the data list
}

Example with source()

source("/Users/Daniel/BRT/Code/R/readFiles.R")
l <- readFiles("./data", pattern = ".csv")

Lab (requires using last skills from last week)

  • Load the longley dataset (from ./data)
  • Write a function that fits 3 simple linear regression models, with GNP, Armed.Forces, and Population as predictors of Employed. Return the output from each in a list, of class mods. Run the function and store the output in an object, regs.
  • Write a default plot method for objects of class mods, which displays three scatter plots (using par(mfrow = c(3,1)) and the regression line for each). Execute the function then run plot(regs). If you do not get the three regression plots, you have an error.
  • Write an infix function that tests whether the mean of one vector is within a standard deviation of the mean of the second vector. Test the function with Unemployed and Armed.Forces.

Load longley dataset, write regression function and store results in

regs.

long <- read.csv("./data/longley.csv")

## Warning in file(file, "rt"): cannot open file './data/longley.csv': No such
## file or directory

## Error in file(file, "rt"): cannot open the connection

mods <- function(d) {
    gnp <- lm(Employed ~ GNP, data = d)
    af <- lm(Employed ~ Armed.Forces, data = d)
    pop <- lm(Employed ~ Population, data = d)

    l <- list(GNP = gnp, ArmedForces = af, Population = pop)
return(structure(l, class = "mods")) 
}
regs <- mods(long)

Produce default plot for class mods.

plot.mods <- function(modList) {
    regPlot <- function(mod) {
        plot(mod$model[[2]], mod$model[[1]])
        abline(coef(mod)[1], coef(mod)[2], lwd = 2, col = "blue", lty = 2)
    }

    par(mfrow = c(3, 1))
    regPlot(modList[[1]])
    regPlot(modList[[2]])
    regPlot(modList[[3]])
}

Issues with this plot

  • x-axes differ, y-axes could (though they don't appear to here)
  • Labels are not very informative
  • Doesn't display any uncertainty of the regression line
  • Others?
plot(regs)

Infix function

`%/>%` <- function(x, y) {
    mx <- mean(x, na.rm = TRUE)
    my <- mean(y, na.rm = TRUE)
    sdy <- sd(y, na.rm = TRUE)

    mx >= my - sdy & mx <= my + sdy
}

mean(longley$Unemployed)

## [1] 319.3313

mean(longley$Armed.Forces) - sd(longley$Armed.Forces)

## [1] 191.0768

mean(longley$Armed.Forces) + sd(longley$Armed.Forces)

## [1] 330.2607



longley$Unemployed %/>% longley$Armed.Forces

## [1] TRUE
